        "excerpt": "Chrome at work. Safari on your phone. Firefox at home. Your bookmarks shouldn't care which browser you're in.",
        "content": "\n# How to Sync Bookmarks Across All My Devices in 2026\n\nI use Chrome at work, Safari on my iPhone, and Edge at home. Three browsers, three separate bookmark worlds.\n\nEvery time I saved something at work, I'd email myself the link just so I could find it on my phone. That's not a system. That's a cry for help.\n\n## Why Browser Sync Doesn't Cut It\n\nChrome syncs Chrome bookmarks. Safari syncs Safari bookmarks. They don't talk to each other.\n\nIf you're a one-browser person, native sync works fine. But most of us aren't.\n\n## The Cross-Browser Solution\n\n[Markify](https://markify.tech) doesn't care what browser you use. It has extensions for Chrome, Safari, Firefox, and Edge. Your collection lives in one place.\n\nSave on your work laptop in Chrome → find it on your commute in Safari → reference it at home in Edge. Same bookmarks, everywhere.\n\n## What About xBrowserSync?\n\nxBrowserSync is open-source and free. It syncs across browsers with encryption. The downside: no visual previews, no AI tagging, basic interface. But for privacy-focused users, it's excellent.\n\n## My Setup\n\nI stopped thinking about which browser I'm using. Save to Markify from anything, anywhere. The bookmarks just follow me.\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n### Does sync work on mobile?\nYes. [Markify](https://markify.tech) mobile apps sync automatically.\n\n### Is my data encrypted during sync?\nYes. All major tools use encryption for cloud sync.\n\n### What if I lose internet?\nMost tools cache locally. You can browse existing bookmarks offline and sync when reconnected.\n    ",
