        "content": "\n# Best Twitter Bookmark Manager 2026\n\nI've got 800+ Twitter bookmarks. Threads about startups, design tips, coding tutorials, hilarious screenshots.\n\nCan I find any of them? Absolutely not.\n\nTwitter's bookmark feature is a chronological dumping ground with no search, no tags, no folders. They built it like an afterthought because it was one.\n\n## Why Twitter Bookmarks Need Rescuing\n\n**No search.** The most basic feature. Scroll through hundreds of bookmarks to find one tweet. Good luck.\n\n**No organization.** Everything in one flat list. That startup advice thread lives next to a meme.\n\n**Limited storage.** Twitter doesn't tell you, but there's a cap. Old bookmarks silently disappear.\n\n## 1. Markify (Best for Saving Tweets)\n\n[Markify](https://markify.tech) saves any tweet URL as a visual bookmark. The tweet text and author are captured in the thumbnail. Tag it, find it later.\n\nI tag mine by topic: `#startup-advice`, `#design-inspo`, `#dev-tips`. Six months of tweets, searchable in seconds.\n\n## 2. Dewey (Best Twitter-Specific Tool)\n\nDewey is built exclusively for Twitter bookmarks. It imports your bookmarks and applies AI categorization. Great if Twitter is your only source.\n\n## 3. Readwise (Best for Highlights)\n\nReadwise captures highlights from tweets and threads, syncing them to note-taking apps. Different purpose—reading retention rather than link organization.\n\n## My Twitter Save System\n\nSee great tweet → copy tweet URL → save to [Markify](https://markify.tech) with topic tag → done. Ten seconds.\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n### Can Markify save entire Twitter threads?\nYou can save the thread URL and Markify captures the first tweet as a preview.\n\n### Does Dewey work with X/Twitter?\nYes, same platform, updated branding.\n\n### What about Twitter Blue's bookmark folders?\nThey exist, but they're basic. No search, limited categorization.\n    ",
