        "content": "\n# How to Manage X (Twitter) Bookmarks 2026\n\nX, formerly Twitter, rebranded everything. New name, new logo, new pricing.\n\nBut the bookmark system? Exactly the same unsearchable mess it's always been.\n\nHere's how to actually manage your X bookmarks in 2026.\n\n## The Current State of X Bookmarks\n\nX Premium (formerly Blue) added bookmark folders. That's the only organizational improvement in years. No search within bookmarks. No tagging. No export.\n\nFor a platform where people share some of the most valuable professional content on the internet, the bookmark system is embarrassingly basic.\n\n## Export and Organize Externally\n\nThe smartest approach: don't rely on X's built-in system at all.\n\n1. **Save tweet URLs to [Markify](https://markify.tech)** as you find good content\n2. **Tag by topic** — the AI handles initial tagging\n3. **Search later** — find any saved tweet in seconds\n\n## Why External Tools Win\n\nX could delete your bookmarks tomorrow. You don't own that data.\n\nWhen you save to an external tool, those bookmarks are yours. Cross-platform, backed up, searchable.\n\n## Thread Saving Strategy\n\nLong threads are where the real value lives on X. Save the first tweet of the thread—that's the thread URL. Add a note: \"Great thread about pricing strategy, 15 tweets.\"\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n### Can I export all my X bookmarks at once?\nX doesn't offer native export. Third-party tools like Dewey can import your bookmarks.\n\n### Will X eventually improve bookmarks?\nMaybe. But waiting for platform features is a losing game. Use external tools now.\n\n### Is it safe to use third-party tools with X?\nYes, as long as they only require your bookmark URLs—not your login credentials.\n    ",
