        "title": "Bookmark Managers for Collaboration",
        "slug": "bookmark-managers-for-collaboration",
        "excerpt": "Your team shares links in Slack. They disappear in a day. Here's how shared bookmark collections save everyone time.",
        "content": "\n# Bookmark Managers for Collaboration\n\nEvery team has that Slack channel. \"Useful links.\" \"Resources.\" \"#stuff-we-might-need.\"\n\nSix months in, 400 links buried in chat history. Nobody can find anything.\n\nSlack is a conversation tool—not a knowledge base.\n\n## Why Shared Bookmarks Beat Slack Links\n\n**They don't scroll away.** A shared collection stays permanent and searchable.\n\n**Context survives.** Tags and notes explain *why* a link matters, not just what it is.\n\n**No duplicates.** Five people won't share the same article because everyone sees what's already saved.\n\n## Team Bookmark Collections That Work\n\n[Markify](https://markify.tech) lets you create shared collections. Everyone on the team can add, tag, and search.\n\nHere's how my team organizes:\n\n- **\"Competitor Research\"** — competitor features, pricing, blog posts\n- **\"Design System\"** — UI patterns, component libraries, guidelines\n- **\"Onboarding\"** — everything new hires need in one place\n\n## The Multiplier Effect\n\nOne person saves a useful link, the entire team benefits. Over months, your shared collection becomes a curated knowledge base that compounds.\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n### Can team members have different permissions?\nYes. [Markify](https://markify.tech) supports viewer and editor roles.\n\n### Does this replace Notion or Confluence?\nNo. Markify handles web links. Notion/Confluence handles internal docs. Different purposes.\n\n### How many people can share a collection?\nNo per-seat limits on collection access.\n    ",
