        "slug": "export-import-bookmarks-guide",
        "excerpt": "Switching tools? Migrating browsers? Here's the complete guide to moving your bookmarks without losing anything.",
        "content": "\n# Export/Import Bookmarks Guide\n\nMoving your bookmarks between tools shouldn't feel like moving apartments. But without a guide, it kind of does.\n\nHere's how to export and import bookmarks across every major browser and tool.\n\n## Exporting from Browsers\n\n### Chrome\n1. Go to `chrome://bookmarks`\n2. Click the three-dot menu (top right)\n3. Select \"Export bookmarks\"\n4. Save the HTML file\n\n### Firefox\n1. Bookmarks → Show All Bookmarks\n2. Import and Backup → Export Bookmarks to HTML\n\n### Safari\n1. File → Export Bookmarks\n2. Choose save location\n\n### Edge\n1. Settings → Profiles → Import browser data\n2. Or export to HTML from `edge://favorites`\n\n## Importing into Bookmark Managers\n\n### Markify\n\n[Markify](https://markify.tech) supports HTML import from any browser. Upload your file and bookmarks appear with preserved folder structure.\n\n### Raindrop.io\n\nImport via Settings → Import. Supports HTML and CSV.\n\n## Tips for Clean Migration\n\n**Clean up before exporting.** Delete duplicates and dead links first.\n**Test import with a small batch.** Export a single folder first to verify format.\n**Keep the HTML backup.** Even after successful import, keep the export file.\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n### Will I lose my folder structure?\nMost tools preserve folder hierarchy. [Markify](https://markify.tech) converts folders to collections.\n\n### Can I import from multiple browsers?\nYes. Import from each browser separately. Duplicates are usually handled automatically.\n\n### What format should I export in?\nHTML is the universal standard. Every browser and tool supports it.\n    ",
