        "content": "\n# Save and Categorize Web Pages\n\nSaving a web page takes one second. Finding it three months later? That's where systems either work or fail.\n\nMost people save links like they'll remember where they put them. Spoiler: they won't.\n\n## The Save-and-Forget Trap\n\nYou find a great article. Ctrl+D. Saved. Feeling productive.\n\nThree months later: \"Where was that thing about pricing strategies?\"\n\nYou don't remember the title. You don't remember the website. You don't remember when you saved it. Your 600-bookmark folder offers zero help.\n\n## The Better Way\n\n**Save with context, not just the URL.** Add a quick note: why did you save this? What's the key takeaway?\n\n**Let AI categorize.** [Markify](https://markify.tech) auto-tags based on page content. A pricing article gets tagged `#pricing`, `#strategy`, `#business` without you doing anything.\n\n**Search instead of browse.** Type what you remember. Good search finds the rest.\n\n## Tools That Save and Categorize Well\n\n**Markify** — One-click save with automatic categorization. Best for most people.\n\n**Raindrop.io** — Manual categorization with powerful folders. Best for control freaks.\n\n**Pocket** — Save articles for reading. Limited categorization.\n\n## Frequently Asked Questions\n\n### Does auto-categorization actually work?\nYes. [Markify](https://markify.tech) gets it right about 85% of the time. You can adjust easily.\n\n### Should I categorize everything?\nNo. Save everything, but only manually categorize what's important. Let AI handle the rest.\n\n### How do I handle pages that fit multiple categories?\nUse tags instead of folders. One bookmark, multiple tags.\n    ",
